This section constitutes the Software Maintenance Plan as required by
EN 50716:2023, Clause 9.2 and Table A.1 (document 42). It defines the
strategy, processes, and techniques governing all post-deployment changes
to the software throughout the operational lifetime of the system.
<<<

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Maintenance scope and objectives

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: DM-100
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Maintenance scope and objectives
STATEMENT: >>>
The Software Maintenance Plan covers all post-deployment changes to the
software for the system identified in the document information section,
throughout its operational lifetime.

Maintenance categories:

  Corrective maintenance: resolution of defects and anomalies discovered
    during operation, including safety-related and non-safety defects.

  Adaptive maintenance: modifications required due to changes in the
    operational environment — hardware obsolescence, operating system
    updates, changes to adjacent systems or external interfaces.

  Perfective maintenance: improvements to performance, maintainability,
    or functionality that do not arise from a defect or external change.

  Emergency maintenance: urgent corrective action required to address a
    safety-critical defect or failure in the operational system.

Maintenance objectives:
  a) Ensure the software continues to meet its safety requirements
     throughout its operational lifetime.
  b) Ensure all changes are controlled, verified, and documented in
     accordance with EN 50716:2023, Clause 9.2.
  c) Ensure the integrity of the safety case is maintained after each change.
  d) Prevent the introduction of new defects through the maintenance process.

Responsible parties:
  Maintenance Manager:     <Name, Organisation>
  Safety Manager:          <Name, Organisation>
  Change Authority:        <Name / Role — approves change requests>
  Maintenance Implementer: <Name / team>
  Maintenance Verifier:    <Name, Organisation — independent of implementer>

Maintenance period: from initial deployment through to system decommissioning.
This plan shall be reviewed at least every <n> years or following any Major
modification.
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Clause 9.2 and Table A.1, doc 42 – Software Maintenance Plan.

[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Modification classification

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: DM-110
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Major and minor modification classification
STATEMENT: >>>
Every proposed change shall be classified as Major or Minor before
implementation. The classification determines the required lifecycle activities
and the extent of re-verification and re-validation.

Major modification — definition:
  A modification is Major if it meets any of the following criteria:
  a) Changes to safety-critical software requirements (SRS-xxx).
  b) Changes to safety-critical source code or data structures.
  c) Changes to the software architecture or inter-module interfaces.
  d) Introduction of new safety functions or removal of existing ones.
  e) Changes to timing parameters that affect the safety response time budget.
  f) Changes to the generic software platform version or configuration.
  g) Changes that require re-assessment of the hazard log or safety case.
  h) Any change for which the impact analysis (DM-140) cannot confirm
     isolation to non-safety components.

  Required lifecycle activities for Major modifications:
    - Full impact analysis (DM-140).
    - Update of all affected lifecycle documents (SRS, SAD, source, tests).
    - Re-execution of all affected test cases; full regression test suite.
    - Re-verification per EN 50716:2023, Clause 7.6 (as applicable).
    - Re-validation per EN 50716:2023, Clause 7.7 (as applicable).
    - Issue of new release note; new deployment cycle per §2.

Minor modification — definition:
  A change is Minor if it meets all of the following criteria:
  a) Does not affect any safety-critical requirement, function, or parameter.
  b) Does not affect any safety-critical source code path.
  c) Change is limited to non-safety components or documentation.
  d) Impact analysis (DM-140) confirms no effect on safety functions.
  Examples: correction of non-safety text or comments, update of non-safety
  configuration parameters within approved bounds, documentation corrections.

  Required lifecycle activities for Minor modifications:
    - Impact analysis confirming Minor classification.
    - Update of affected documents.
    - Targeted regression tests covering the modified component.
    - Verification inspection (no full re-validation required).
    - Update of maintenance records (DM-170).

Classification disputes: if the classification is disputed or uncertain,
the change shall be treated as Major.
Classification authority: <Name / Role of Change Authority (DM-100)>.
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Clause 9.2 and Table A.1, doc 42 – Software Maintenance Plan.

[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Change control process

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: DM-120
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Change control process
STATEMENT: >>>
All changes to the software shall follow the change control process defined
in SP-061 (Change Control Procedure). The process is summarised below.

Change control lifecycle:

  Step 1 — Change Request (CR):
    A Change Request is raised by any stakeholder using form <CR-form ref>.
    CR fields: description, reason, category (corrective / adaptive /
    perfective / emergency), priority, and submitter.
    CR registered in the change management system: <system reference>.

  Step 2 — Impact analysis (DM-140):
    Impact analysis performed by Maintenance Implementer and reviewed by
    Maintenance Verifier. Results documented in the DCR (DM-160).
    Classification determined per DM-110.

  Step 3 — Change authorisation:
    Change Authority reviews CR, impact analysis, and classification.
    Approves, rejects, or defers the change.
    For emergency maintenance: abbreviated authorisation with retrospective
    full review within <n> working days.

  Step 4 — Implementation:
    Implementer carries out the change per the approved scope.
    All modified source files committed to version control with reference
    to the DCR ID.
    Compilation and static analysis re-run on modified components.

  Step 5 — Testing:
    Test suite re-executed per DM-130 (regression strategy for the
    applicable modification class).
    All affected test cases shall show PASS before proceeding.
    Problem reports (PR-DCR-xxx) raised for any failures.

  Step 6 — Verification:
    Maintenance Verifier performs verification inspection per DM-190.
    Verdict recorded in DCR (DM-160) and Maintenance Verification Report (§8).

  Step 7 — Release:
    For Major modifications: new release note issued; deployment cycle per §2.
    For Minor modifications: update maintenance records (DM-170); no new
    deployment cycle required if change does not affect deployed binary.

  Step 8 — Closure:
    DCR status set to Closed; maintenance records updated (DM-170, DM-180).

Reference: SP-061 — Change Control Procedure.
Emergency maintenance: additional escalation path per SP-062.
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Clause 9.2 and Table A.1, doc 42 – Software Maintenance Plan.

[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Re-validation and regression testing strategy

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: DM-130
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Re-validation and regression testing strategy
STATEMENT: >>>
The extent of re-verification and re-validation required after a modification
is determined by the modification classification (DM-110) and the scope of
the impact analysis (DM-140).

Re-validation strategy by modification class:

  Major modification:
    a) All test cases covering modified requirements shall be re-executed.
    b) Full regression test suite shall be re-executed (all VTR-xxx and
       ATR-xxx test cases as applicable).
    c) Integration tests (ITR-xxx, HITR-xxx) shall be re-executed for any
       modified interfaces.
    d) Performance tests (VAL-031, INT-050) shall be re-executed if timing
       parameters are changed.
    e) Re-validation verdict (DM-200) shall be issued before new release.
    f) Updated release note required (new SW-REL-xxx / APP-REL-xxx).

  Minor modification:
    a) Targeted test cases covering the modified component shall be re-executed.
    b) Regression tests selected by impact analysis (DM-140) shall be executed.
    c) No full re-validation required; verification inspection (DM-190) suffices.

Regression test selection — minimum scope:
  All test cases whose parent requirement is affected by the change (via
  traceability, DM-140) shall be included in the regression set regardless
  of modification class.

Test baseline for regression: test cases from the most recent PASS
validation run (VTR-xxx series, 07_overall_testing_validation.sdoc, or
ATR-xxx series, 08_application_data.sdoc) shall be used as the baseline.

Re-validation authority: same as the original validation authority unless
the Safety Manager approves an alternative verifier.
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Clause 9.2 and Table A.1, doc 42 – Software Maintenance Plan.

[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Impact analysis requirements (Table A.10)

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: DM-140
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Impact analysis requirements
STATEMENT: >>>
Impact analysis shall be performed for every proposed change in accordance
with EN 50716:2023, Table A.10 (Clause 9.2).

Impact analysis scope — the analysis shall determine:

  a) Which safety requirements (SRS-xxx) are affected by the change.
  b) Which software components and modules contain the change.
  c) Which interfaces (internal and external) may be affected.
  d) Whether the change affects any safety function or safety integrity
     level claim.
  e) Whether the change classification is Major or Minor per DM-110.
  f) Which test cases must be re-executed (regression set per DM-130).
  g) Whether the hazard log or safety case requires updating.
  h) Whether any tool qualification evidence requires updating.

Impact analysis method:
  1. Traceability traversal: starting from the changed item, traverse the
     traceability chain (forward and backward) to identify all affected
     requirements, design elements, and test cases.
  2. Dependency check: review inter-module dependencies (APP-070 / SAD)
     for any indirect effects.
  3. Interface check: review all interfaces (internal and external) of
     the modified component for potential propagation of the change.
  4. Safety function check: confirm whether any safety function or its
     contributing components are in the affected set.

Impact analysis documentation (recorded in DCR, DM-160):
  - List of affected requirements (SRS-xxx, APP-xxx, or "none").
  - List of affected components and source files.
  - List of affected test cases (regression set).
  - Classification verdict (Major / Minor) with rationale.
  - Safety function impact: <None / describe>
  - Hazard log update required: <Yes / No>

Impact analysis shall be reviewed and approved by the Maintenance Verifier
before implementation proceeds.
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: M
SIL_4: M
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Analysis, Inspection
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.10 – Impact analysis (Clause 9.2).

[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Data recording and analysis requirements (Table A.10)

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: DM-150
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Data recording and analysis requirements
STATEMENT: >>>
Operational data from deployed systems shall be systematically collected and
analysed throughout the maintenance lifetime, in accordance with EN 50716:2023,
Table A.10 (Clause 9.2).

Data to be recorded:

  a) Fault log data: all fault codes, timestamps, and frequencies extracted
     from the target system diagnostic interface at each scheduled maintenance
     visit or on demand following a reported anomaly.
  b) Event counters: safety-relevant event counters (watchdog resets,
     communication timeouts, safe-state activations) read and recorded.
  c) Anomaly reports: field reports from operations and maintenance staff,
     including descriptions, dates, and conditions of occurrence.
  d) Performance data: cycle time measurements and resource utilisation
     readings (if supported by platform diagnostics).
  e) Environmental records: temperature, humidity, and power quality logs
     from on-board or external monitoring equipment (if available).

Recording frequency:
  Scheduled: <every n months / at each planned maintenance visit>
  Triggered: following any reported anomaly, safe-state activation, or
    watchdog reset within <n> working days.
  Emergency: immediately following any safety-related incident.

Data storage and retention:
  Data stored in: <configuration database / maintenance management system>
  Retention period: lifetime of system.
  Format: <CSV / XML / proprietary tool format — reference>.

Analysis requirements:
  Recorded data shall be analysed to:
  - Detect trends indicating degradation or ageing of hardware or software.
  - Identify patterns of recurring faults that may indicate a systematic
    software defect requiring corrective maintenance.
  - Confirm that no safety-relevant events have exceeded their expected
    frequency or changed in character.
  - Feed into the periodic safety review per <SP-070 reference>.

Analysis reporting: data analysis summary shall be included in each
periodic maintenance record (DM-170) and reviewed by the Safety Manager.
Analysis tool: <tool name, version — for fault log extraction and trending>.
<<<
